         </div>
         <div type="translation" ana="#b1" xml:id="jeru0036.translation" corresp="#jeru0036.transcription">
            <p>the amputated (the one-handed)(?)</p>
         </div>
      <div type="edition" subtype="transcription_segmented"><p><w xml:id="jeru0036-1" xml:lang="arc">הגדם</w></p>
</div>
</body>
      <back>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>Ossuary has inner ledge on three sides and traces of red wash. Height refers to height of chest plus that of vaulted lid. Broken lid is sliding, with heights of ends unequal. Ornamentation, on all four sides of the chest, consists of thin doubled lines on edges, each side perhaps representing an ashlar. On the chest's front, two metopes, each containing a six-petalled rosette within a line circle, and a zigzag rosette. Inscription is written in large letters on the chest's back side. הגדם is a nickname in status emphaticus. Such derogatory nicknames were common (as in "the lame one," "the deaf one," "the hunchback," "the stammerer"), and some became family names.</p>
         </div>
